  ---
  Docker — the foundation everything else builds on

  The core idea is simple: instead of saying "deploy my code," you say "deploy
  this exact environment my code runs in."

  Without Docker, deployment goes wrong because of this:
  - Works on your machine (Node 20, yarn 1.22, specific native dependencies)
  - Fails on the server (Node 18, npm, different OS libraries)

  A Dockerfile describes a complete, frozen environment:

  FROM node:20-alpine
  WORKDIR /app
  COPY package.json yarn.lock ./
  COPY packages/nextjs/package.json ./packages/nextjs/
  COPY packages/hardhat/package.json ./packages/hardhat/
  RUN yarn install --frozen-lockfile
  COPY . .
  RUN yarn workspace @tracefund/nextjs build
  EXPOSE 3000
  CMD ["yarn", "workspace", "@tracefund/nextjs", "start"]

  When this builds into an image, it's a complete snapshot: the OS, the Node
  version, your dependencies, your compiled app. That image runs identically on
  your laptop, your collaborator's laptop, AWS, Google Cloud, anywhere. The
  environment is no longer an assumption — it's a contract.

  This is why companies adopted Docker so aggressively. Before it, "it works in
  staging but not prod" was a constant, expensive problem.

  ---
  ECR — Elastic Container Registry

  Think of this as GitHub but for Docker images instead of code.

  Once you build your Docker image locally, you need somewhere to store it so
  AWS can pull it. ECR is AWS's private Docker registry. The flow is:

  Your machine → build image → push to ECR → AWS pulls from ECR → runs it

  Why ECR specifically instead of Docker Hub (the public registry):
  - Your image stays inside AWS's network — faster pulls, no egress costs
  - Private by default — nobody else can pull your image
  - Integrated with IAM, so ECS has permission to pull images automatically
  - Versioned — you push image tags (e.g. v1.0, latest, git-sha) and can roll
  back instantly

  For this project, your ECR repository would store every version of the
  TraceFund frontend image you've ever built.

  ---
  ECS — Elastic Container Service

  ECS is the orchestrator — it answers the question "how do I actually run this
  container, and what happens if it crashes?"

  You define two things:

  Task Definition — a blueprint for your container:
  - Which ECR image to use
  - How much CPU and RAM to allocate
  - Which environment variables to inject
  - What port to expose (3000 for Next.js)
  - Where to send logs (CloudWatch)

  Service — keeps your task running:
  - "Always keep 2 copies of this task running"
  - If one crashes, ECS automatically starts a replacement
  - When you deploy a new image, ECS does a rolling update — starts new
  containers, verifies they're healthy, then kills the old ones. Zero downtime.

  This is what replaces PM2 on EC2. With EC2 you're manually keeping a process
  alive. With ECS it's declarative — you describe what you want running, ECS
  ensures it stays that way.

  ---
  Fargate — the reason you don't manage servers

  ECS needs compute to actually run containers. Historically that meant managing
  a fleet of EC2 instances yourself — patching them, sizing them, handling
  failures. Fargate removes that entirely.

  With Fargate, you tell ECS:
  - "I need 0.5 vCPU and 1 GB of RAM for this container"

  Fargate provisions the compute, runs your container, and you never SSH into
  anything. When the container stops, you stop paying. AWS manages the
  underlying servers completely.

  The real-world analogy: EC2 is renting a whole apartment. Fargate is renting a
  hotel room only when you need it. You don't manage the building — you just
  use the room.

  Cost for TraceFund at low traffic: roughly $15–30/month for a single Fargate
  task running 24/7. Scales to near-zero cost if you stop the service.

  ---
  How the full architecture looks for TraceFund

  User's browser
       ↓
  CloudFront (CDN — caches static assets, handles HTTPS)
       ↓
  Application Load Balancer (routes traffic, health checks)
       ↓
  ECS Service (Fargate) — 1–2 tasks running your Next.js container
       ↓
  ECR (pulls the image on deploy)
       ↓
  Base Mainnet RPC (for blockchain reads — no AWS involvement here)

  ---
  Why this simulates real companies

  Every major tech company runs some version of this stack. The specific
  orchestrator varies (some use Kubernetes instead of ECS, some use GCP instead
  of AWS), but the concepts are identical:

  - Containerize the app — reproducible, portable
  - Push to a registry — versioned, centralized
  - Declare what should run — not "start this process," but "keep this service
  alive"
  - Serverless compute — don't manage VMs, just specify resource requirements
  - Load balancer in front — handles HTTPS, health checks, traffic distribution

  When you learn this stack, you can walk into any engineering team using AWS
  and understand their deployment pipeline immediately. The same mental model
  applies to GKE on Google Cloud and AKS on Azure.

  ---
  The honest trade-offs

  You will need to set up:
  - IAM roles (ECS needs permission to pull from ECR, write to CloudWatch)
  - A VPC with public/private subnets (where the containers actually live in the
  network)
  - An Application Load Balancer with a target group
  - Security groups (firewall rules — ALB talks to Fargate, Fargate talks to the
