⏺ Great question. Let me explain this from the ground up, the way someone
  actually working in this industry thinks about it.

  ---
  The Problem Docker Solves

  Before containers existed, deploying software looked like this:

  A developer writes code on their MacBook. It works perfectly. They hand it to
  the ops team to deploy to a Linux server. It breaks. Why? Because the
  developer's Mac has:
  - Node 20.1
  - A specific version of OpenSSL
  - Environment variables set in their shell profile
  - Native dependencies compiled for macOS

  The server has:
  - Node 18.3
  - A different OpenSSL version
  - No environment variables
  - A different CPU architecture

  The famous phrase that came from this era: "Works on my machine." It became a
  running joke in the industry because it happened constantly and was genuinely
  expensive to debug.

  Docker's answer was: stop shipping code, start shipping the entire environment
  the code runs in.

  ---
  What a Docker Image Actually Is

  A Docker image is not just your code. It is a complete, frozen, layered
  snapshot of:

  - The operating system (usually a minimal Linux — Alpine Linux is 5MB)
  - The runtime (Node.js 20, Python 3.11, Java 17 — whatever your app needs)
  - Your dependencies (everything in node_modules, compiled exactly once)
  - Your compiled application (the Next.js build output)
  - The command to start it (yarn workspace @tracefund/nextjs start)

  When you build an image, all of that gets frozen into a single artifact. Think
  of it like a snapshot of a perfectly configured computer at the exact moment
  your app is ready to run.

  That image can then be shipped anywhere — your laptop, your collaborator's
  laptop, AWS, Google Cloud, a data center in Tokyo — and it runs identically
  every time. The environment is no longer an assumption. It is a guarantee.

  ---
  The Difference Between an Image and a Container

  This trips people up constantly, so here it is clearly:

  - An image is the blueprint. It is static. It sits in a registry.
  - A container is a running instance of that image. It is alive. It uses CPU
  and RAM.

  The relationship is exactly like a class and an object in programming. The
  image is the class definition. The container is the instantiated object
  running in memory.

  You can run five containers from the same image simultaneously. They are all
  identical at startup. You can kill one and start another. The image does not
  change.

  ---
  Why Layers Matter

  This is the part most tutorials skip, but it is what makes Docker genuinely
  fast and efficient in practice.

  A Docker image is not one big file. It is a stack of layers, each representing
  one instruction in the Dockerfile:

  FROM node:20-alpine          ← Layer 1: base OS + Node runtime
  WORKDIR /app                 ← Layer 2: set working directory
  COPY package.json yarn.lock  ← Layer 3: copy dependency manifests
  RUN yarn install             ← Layer 4: install dependencies (LARGE layer)
  COPY . .                     ← Layer 5: copy your source code
  RUN yarn build               ← Layer 6: compile the Next.js app
  CMD ["yarn", "start"]        ← Layer 7: startup command

  Here is why this is critical: Docker caches every layer. If Layer 5 changes
  (you edited a component), Docker does not rebuild Layers 1–4. It reuses the
  cached versions and only reruns Layers 5–7.

  This means:
  - Your first build: 4 minutes (installing all dependencies)
  - Every subsequent build where you only changed code: 20 seconds (dependencies
  are cached)
  - If you change package.json and add a dependency: Docker invalidates the
  cache at Layer 3 and rebuilds from there

  This is why the order of instructions in a Dockerfile matters. You always copy
  package.json before copying your source code, so a code change does not force
  a full dependency reinstall. This is a real engineering decision that affects
  how fast your team can ship.

  ---
  What ECR Is Actually Doing

  ECR (Elastic Container Registry) is essentially GitHub for images.

  When you push code to GitHub, you are storing versioned snapshots of your
  source code. When you push an image to ECR, you are storing versioned
  snapshots of your entire built application environment.

  Every image gets a tag:

  123456789.dkr.ecr.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/tracefund:latest
  123456789.dkr.ecr.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/tracefund:v1.2.0
  123456789.dkr.ecr.us-east-1.amazonaws.com/tracefund:git-a3f9c12

  The last one is what production teams actually use — tagging by the git commit
  SHA. Now you have a permanent, auditable link between the code that was
  committed and the image that was deployed. If something breaks in production,
  you can say "we're running commit a3f9c12, let me look at that diff" and you
  know exactly what changed.

  Rolling back is then trivial: tell ECS to pull the previous image tag. No
  rebuilding. No redeploying code. You're just swapping which frozen snapshot is
  running.

  ---
  What ECS and Fargate Are Actually Doing

  Imagine you hired someone whose only job is to answer one question all day:
  "Is the app running?"

  If the app crashes, they restart it. If traffic spikes and one copy isn't
  enough, they start more copies. If you want to deploy a new version, they
  start the new version, confirm it is healthy, then shut down the old version —
  so there is never a moment where users see a broken state.

  That is ECS. It is an orchestrator. It is not the compute itself — it is the
  manager that decides what should be running and makes sure it stays that way.

  Fargate is the compute underneath. When ECS decides "I need to run the
  TraceFund container," Fargate provides the actual CPU and RAM to do it,
  completely invisibly. You never SSH into a server. You never patch an
  operating system. You never worry about what happens if the underlying
  hardware fails. AWS handles all of that. You just declare what you want
  running.

  The combination works like this:

  You define: "Keep 2 copies of tracefund:latest running,
               each with 0.5 vCPU and 1GB RAM,
               restart if they crash,
               deploy new versions with zero downtime"

  ECS + Fargate: makes that true and keeps it true indefinitely

  ---
  Why Real Companies Use This

  The reason this stack became the industry standard is not because it is the
  simplest option. It is because it solves a set of problems that become
  extremely painful at scale:

  Reproducibility. When a bug appears in production, you can pull the exact
  image that is running, run it locally, and reproduce the problem. You are not
  guessing about what environment prod is in.

  Isolation. Two different services can run on the same hardware without
  interfering. The TraceFund frontend and a hypothetical backend API can have
  completely different Node versions, dependency trees, and environment
  variables, running side by side.

  Scalability. If TraceFund suddenly gets featured somewhere and traffic spikes,
  ECS can start five more containers in under a minute. Then scale back down
  when traffic drops. You pay only for what you run.

  Auditability. Every deploy is a specific image tag tied to a specific git
  commit. You always know exactly what is running in production and can answer
  "what changed between this deploy and the last one" definitively.

  Portability. The Dockerfile you write for AWS works on Google Cloud, Azure, a
  bare metal server, your local machine. You are not locked into one platform's
  proprietary tooling.

  ---
  The Mental Model to Keep

  The way to think about all of this in one sentence:

  Docker packages your app. ECR stores and versions those packages. ECS decides 
  how many to run and where. Fargate provides the invisible compute that 
  actually runs them.

  Each layer has exactly one job. That separation is why the system is reliable
  at scale and why understanding it makes you genuinely useful on any
  engineering team deploying software in 2025.

