  What the RPC URL is for:
  When someone opens the app, the frontend needs to talk to the Base Mainnet
  blockchain to read campaign data (balances, milestones, donations). It does
  that by sending requests to an RPC endpoint — basically a server that speaks
  to the blockchain on your behalf. Without it the app still works, it just
  falls back to Base's free public endpoint which gets rate-limited if multiple
  people are hitting it at the same time. For a demo with multiple wallets, a
  dedicated URL keeps reads reliable.

  What was broken:

  The value sitting in your .env was:

  NEXT_PUBLIC_BASE_RPC_URL=ra9iT20aBzKjLvNKinutm

  That's not a URL — a URL has to start with https://. That string by itself is
  just the API key. The app can't make an HTTP request to ra9iT20aBzKjLvNKinutm
  — there's no address there.

  The full URL Alchemy gives you looks like:

  https://base-mainnet.g.alchemy.com/v2/ra9iT20aBzKjLvNKinutm

  The key is the last part after /v2/. Someone had saved just the key fragment
  into the .env.local.example instead of the whole thing.

  I already fixed it in .env.local — prepended the Alchemy base URL so it's now
  a valid HTTPS address. That's all that changed. If you go into Alchemy, click
  your app, and copy the full HTTPS URL, it should match exactly what's now in
  .env.local.

